"use strict";(globalThis.webpackChunkacp_documentation=globalThis.webpackChunkacp_documentation||[]).push([[6071],{6724(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('{"archive":{"blogPosts":[{"id":"/2026/03/16/slurm","metadata":{"permalink":"/acp-documentation/blog/2026/03/16/slurm","editUrl":"https://github.com/facebook/docusaurus/tree/main/packages/create-docusaurus/templates/shared/blog/2026-03-16-slurm.md","source":"@site/blog/2026-03-16-slurm.md","title":"Official ACP SLURM Restructuring & 2026 System Updates","description":"The SLURM restructuring for the ACP is officially complete. We have transitioned away from complex partition naming to a simplified model designed for maximum efficiency and fairness. These updates ensure that all researchers have equitable access to our high-performance resources.","date":"2026-03-16T00:00:00.000Z","tags":[{"inline":true,"label":"announcement","permalink":"/acp-documentation/blog/tags/announcement"},{"inline":true,"label":"hpc","permalink":"/acp-documentation/blog/tags/hpc"},{"inline":true,"label":"slurm","permalink":"/acp-documentation/blog/tags/slurm"},{"inline":true,"label":"montera","permalink":"/acp-documentation/blog/tags/montera"}],"readingTime":2.45,"hasTruncateMarker":true,"authors":[{"name":"Montage Team","title":"High Performance Computing Team","url":"https://github.com/monash-acp","imageURL":"https://github.com/monash-acp.png","socials":{},"key":null,"page":null}],"frontMatter":{"title":"Official ACP SLURM Restructuring & 2026 System Updates","authors":[{"name":"Montage Team","title":"High Performance Computing Team","url":"https://github.com/monash-acp","imageURL":"https://github.com/monash-acp.png"}],"tags":["announcement","hpc","slurm","montera"],"date":"2026-03-16T00:00:00.000Z"},"unlisted":false},"content":"The SLURM restructuring for the ACP is officially complete. We have transitioned away from complex partition naming to a simplified model designed for maximum efficiency and fairness. These updates ensure that all researchers have equitable access to our high-performance resources.\\n\\n\x3c!--truncate--\x3e\\n\\n## 1. Simplified Partitions\\n\\nWe have consolidated all compute nodes into two primary partitions. If your `.sbatch` scripts still use legacy names, your jobs will not start. Please update your scripts to use:\\n\\n- **`cpu`**: General-purpose CPU computing nodes.\\n- **`gpu`**: High-performance GPU-accelerated nodes.\\n\\n## 2. Training and Dashboard Demo\\n\\nTo help everyone adapt to these changes, we urge all users to join our upcoming training session. We will be demoing the new **MONTERA All-in-1** dashboard, which will soon feature real-time CPU% and Memory% usage tracking.\\n\\n**Sign up for Training**: [https://forms.gle/HLreQ2kXnTgFUPAr9](https://forms.gle/HLreQ2kXnTgFUPAr9)\\n\\nMonitoring your job\'s efficiency is critical. If your code shows 0% CPU utilization, it is a sign of an error or a hang, and the job should be terminated immediately to avoid resource hogging.\\n\\n## 3. The Priority Game (QoS)\\n\\nYour job\'s priority and duration are now defined by the Quality of Service (QoS) flag:\\n\\n- **`short`**: 2-hour limit. Use this for high-priority tests and debugging. \\n- **`normal`**: The default setting with a 7-day partition limit.\\n- **`long`**: For 28-day marathons. These have lower priority but are protected from preemption.\\n\\n## 4. Memory & Fairness Model\\n\\nOur new fairness model rewards users who request smaller resource footprints. Requesting excessive RAM relative to CPU cores will lower your fairshare priority and increase your wait time.\\n\\n- **Default Allocation**: 4GB per CPU.\\n- **Maximum Recommended**: 16GB per CPU.\\n\\n## 5. CPU Spillover and Efficiency\\n\\nTo ensure the cluster remains efficient, we have implemented a spillover policy for CPU jobs:\\n- **Jobs \\\\<= 1 Day**: can execute on both CPU nodes (`mum-hpc2-comp[1-4]`) and idle GPU nodes (`mum-hpc2-gpu[1-4]`).\\n- **Jobs \\\\> 1 Day**: remain strictly on CPU nodes to protect GPU resources for researchers who require them.\\n\\n## 6. High-Performance GPU Hardware\\n\\nThe `gpu` partition has been updated with high-end hardware for public use:\\n- **A100 GPUs**: Available on nodes `gpu5` and `gpu6`.\\n- **H100 GPUs**: Available on nodes `gpu7` and `gpu8`.\\n\\nThese specific nodes have **no Multi-Instance GPU (MIG)** configured, providing full access to the hardware for parallel GPU training. To request these, use `--gpus=a100:1` or `--gpus=h100:1` in your scripts.\\n\\n## 7. Script Checkout\\n\\nEnsure your Slurm scripts reflect the new rules to avoid queuing delays:\\n\\n```bash\\n#SBATCH --partition=cpu           # Options: cpu, gpu \\n#SBATCH --qos=short               # High-priority tests (2hr limit)\\n#SBATCH --cpus-per-task=1         # Standard allocation\\n#SBATCH --mem=4G                  # Fairshare-friendly memory\\n#SBATCH --time=2:00:00            # Be accurate to start sooner\\n```\\n\\nThe ACP is currently tuned for maximum throughput. Use the `show_cluster` command to check real-time availability. If you are unclear about any of these rules, we will be available during the training session to guide you."}]}}')}}]);